& \Rightarrow 2 I=\int_{0}^{\frac{\pi}{2}} \frac{\sin ^{2} x+\sin x+\cos ^{2} x+\cos x}{\sin x+\cos x+1} \mathrm{dx}=\int_{0}^{\frac{\pi}{2}} \frac{1+\sin x+\cos x}{\sin x+\cos x+1} \mathrm{dx}=\int_{0}^{\frac{\pi}{2}} 1 d x=\frac{\pi}{2} \Rightarrow I=\frac{\pi}{4}
\end{aligned}
$$

Solution. $r=\ln e^{t}-\ln \left(e^{t}+1\right)=t-\ln \left(e^{t}+1\right)$;

$$
\frac{d r}{d t}=1-\frac{\left(e^{t}+1\right)^{\prime}}{e^{t}+1}=1-\frac{e^{t}}{e^{t}+1}=\frac{1}{e^{t}+1}
$$

